WEBVTT

00:22.147 --> 00:29.112
♪ (OPERA MUSIC PLAYS) ♪

00:34.993 --> 00:39.038
(TRAM SIGNAL RINGS)

00:47.046 --> 00:53.970
(TRAM WHEELS SQUEAL)

00:55.555 --> 00:56.806
DIRECTOR: Left stage!

01:00.435 --> 01:01.686
DIRECTOR: Action! Rain.

01:02.395 --> 01:07.192
♪ (MUSIC CONTINUES) ♪

01:09.861 --> 01:11.321
(TRAM SIGNAL RINGS)

01:12.155 --> 01:13.740
DIRECTOR: Market Square, action!

01:14.699 --> 01:16.201
Action!

01:16.284 --> 01:19.412
♪ (MUSIC CONTINUES) ♪

01:25.752 --> 01:27.754
-(CELLPHONE RINGS)
-DOUGLAS HYLTON: Uh-huh.

01:27.837 --> 01:29.088
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

01:29.172 --> 01:30.924
-DOUGLAS: Ah... Shit.
-(CELLPHONE RINGS)

01:31.841 --> 01:34.469
-DOUGLAS: Ah.
-(CELLPHONE RINGS)

01:34.552 --> 01:35.845
Uh... Hello? Douglas speaking.

01:35.929 --> 01:37.555
SUSAN EDWARDS: (OVER PHONE)
Oh, hello. It's Susan Edwards.

01:37.639 --> 01:39.265
I understand you're being
offered as-- as my, um...

01:39.349 --> 01:41.100
DOUGLAS: Yes, that's right.
My name is Douglas Hylton.

01:41.184 --> 01:43.186
I'll be coming in to help you
tonight, Mrs. Edwards.

01:43.269 --> 01:44.521
SUSAN: Oh, Susan's fine.

01:44.604 --> 01:46.314
DOUGLAS: Oh. Okay, thanks. Um...

01:46.397 --> 01:48.733
Well, if you'd like,
I'll be representing you

01:48.817 --> 01:50.318
-for the foreseeable--
-SUSAN: Oh, good, because...

01:50.401 --> 01:52.237
you've heard, I think,
that my husband and I

01:52.320 --> 01:54.948
have got ourselves
into a bit of a pickle.

01:55.031 --> 01:57.075
-I know it sounds all rather...
-DOUGLAS: Susan. Susan?

01:57.158 --> 01:58.535
-...morbid--
-Uh-- Sorry to interrupt you,

01:58.618 --> 02:00.829
and thank you for calling me,
but I'm actually, uh,

02:00.912 --> 02:04.123
walking to you right now,
so if that could just wait
for a minute.

02:04.207 --> 02:06.334
SUSAN: Yeah, I mean,
obviously we regret... I mean--

02:06.417 --> 02:09.420
I mean, we should have done
certain things differently.

02:09.504 --> 02:11.714
I-- I think we're both happy
to admit that.

02:11.798 --> 02:13.633
Well, "ha--" "happy"
is hardly the word, is it?

02:13.716 --> 02:15.718
DOUGLAS: (OVER PHONE)
(CHUCKLES) So-- So--

02:15.802 --> 02:17.887
So, I can hear you've got a lot
to get off your chest,

02:17.971 --> 02:19.180
but, um, really,

02:19.264 --> 02:21.349
-it's, uh...
-It is just very complicated,
Douglas,

02:21.432 --> 02:23.184
and I'm very keen for--

02:23.268 --> 02:24.978
But it's my husband,
really, Chris, he just...

02:25.061 --> 02:26.813
-he shouldn't be here.
-Sus-- Susan? Susan?

02:26.896 --> 02:28.898
-Sorry, can I just--
-So I feel, for his sake,

02:28.982 --> 02:30.483
everyone should know the truth
from the outset.

02:30.567 --> 02:32.360
-Uh... Uh-- Uh-- Susan?
-Yes?

02:32.443 --> 02:34.863
It-- It's-- It's-- It's just...
This isn't a private call

02:34.946 --> 02:37.031
because I'm not actually
your representative yet.

02:37.115 --> 02:38.700
Uh... That's what I'm coming
to do now,

02:38.783 --> 02:40.118
you see,
to take your instruction,

02:40.201 --> 02:41.578
and then I can...

02:41.661 --> 02:43.037
-Does that make sense?
-I see, yes.

02:43.121 --> 02:44.664
-Sorry. Silly old me. (CHUCKLES)
-(CHUCKLES)

02:44.747 --> 02:47.125
-(DOOR SLAMS)
-Look, I-- I can sense
we're gonna get on, Susan.

02:47.208 --> 02:49.335
-I'll speak to you very soon.
-Thank you.

02:51.504 --> 02:53.590
-(INDISTINCT CHATTER)
-(DOOR SLAMS)

02:53.673 --> 02:56.551
-♪ (OPERA MUSIC PLAYS) ♪
-Sorry to keep you.

02:58.803 --> 03:01.764
(DOOR SCREECHES, BOOMS SHUT)

03:01.848 --> 03:06.269
♪ (OPERA MUSIC PLAYS) ♪

03:09.147 --> 03:12.400
-(BELL RINGS)
-(DOOR OPENS)

03:12.483 --> 03:13.902
(DOOR CLOSES)

03:13.985 --> 03:19.574
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

03:25.663 --> 03:28.124
(CLOCK TICKS)

03:28.207 --> 03:30.877
(BOTTLES RATTLE QUIETLY)

03:32.962 --> 03:35.089
-FRANCOIS: Bonjour, Madame.
-Bonjour.

03:36.174 --> 03:37.425
FRANCOIS: (IN FRENCH)

03:37.508 --> 03:39.427
SUSAN: (IN FRENCH)

03:41.220 --> 03:45.600
FRANCOIS: (IN FRENCH)

03:45.683 --> 03:48.353
SUSAN: Ah... (IN FRENCH)

03:48.436 --> 03:50.855
(IN ENGLISH) Of course,
but I think you mentioned

03:50.939 --> 03:53.524
this one.
He's one of your favorites.

03:53.608 --> 03:55.944
(PAPER RUSTLING)

03:56.027 --> 03:58.947
-FRANCOIS: Gary Cooper.
-Oh...

03:59.030 --> 04:01.532
(PAPER RUSTLING)

04:02.158 --> 04:03.284
(GASPS)

04:03.368 --> 04:07.080
It's an original,
from the second Belgian release.

04:07.163 --> 04:09.332
-The second Belgian release?
-Mm-hmm.

04:10.208 --> 04:12.835
(IN FRENCH)

04:12.919 --> 04:14.796
(IN ENGLISH)
Aside from everything else.
(CHUCKLES)

04:14.879 --> 04:17.465
For you, madame,
I'll make a special price.

04:17.548 --> 04:19.676
-Two hundred fifty.
-Oh, no, um,

04:19.759 --> 04:22.929
-Francois, it's too much. Sorry.
-How about 200?

04:23.888 --> 04:25.974
I could possibly stretch
to 100, but...

04:26.057 --> 04:30.812
(INHALES) Madame... (EXHALES)
...for you, I'll make it 150,

04:30.895 --> 04:32.563
'cause I know
this will make you happy

04:32.647 --> 04:36.234
-and that makes me happy too.
-(CHUCKLES)

04:36.317 --> 04:37.735
-(CHUCKLES)
-(CLICKS TONGUE)

04:37.819 --> 04:40.113
Okay. (CHUCKLES)

04:44.909 --> 04:48.788
Uh-- If you use the card,
it must be 170, madame.

04:48.871 --> 04:51.749
Oh, okay. (INHALES)

04:53.793 --> 04:55.503
-SUSAN: Merci.
-Merci beaucoup.

04:55.586 --> 04:56.546
Mm-hmm.

04:56.629 --> 04:58.881
-(LOCK CLICKS)
-♪ (PEACEFUL MUSIC PLAYS) ♪

04:58.965 --> 05:00.591
(HINGES SQUEAK)

05:12.729 --> 05:15.189
-Salut, mon cher.
-(LAUGHS)

05:15.273 --> 05:16.774
-Hello, darling. (KISSES)
-Mm-hmm. (KISSES)

05:16.858 --> 05:18.359
That's a nice greeting.

05:18.443 --> 05:22.322
-Good morning?
-Um... It's okay, I think.

05:22.405 --> 05:23.948
-Lovely.
-(GROANS)

05:24.032 --> 05:26.576
-I've made sandwiches.
-Thank you.

05:26.659 --> 05:29.203
And there's soup
from last night if you want it.

05:29.287 --> 05:31.039
Oh. (CHUCKLES)

05:31.122 --> 05:33.332
-(KEYS THUD ON TABLE)
-CHRISTOPHER EDWARDS:
What's in the sarnies?

05:33.416 --> 05:36.586
Tuna and sweetcorn
on normal bread.

05:37.462 --> 05:38.755
Found some
in the English section

05:38.838 --> 05:40.923
-at the Monoprix.
-Oh, lovely.

05:41.966 --> 05:43.384
(GROANS)

05:44.177 --> 05:47.638
Yes. Yes, yes. I felt I made...

05:47.722 --> 05:49.599
a good impression.
Oh, and my French

05:49.682 --> 05:51.768
-is really improving, actually.
-Ah!

05:51.851 --> 05:53.644
-Drink?
-Yes, please.

05:53.728 --> 05:55.438
So, I've got another one
this afternoon

05:55.521 --> 05:59.025
which I'm hoping
will go even better. Mmm.

06:04.864 --> 06:06.407
Oh, yes. Look, Chris!

06:10.078 --> 06:11.871
It's just like the one
I had on my bedroom wall

06:11.954 --> 06:13.122
-as a little girl...
-(PAPER RUSTLING)

06:13.206 --> 06:14.916
...that my grandfather
brought me.

06:14.999 --> 06:17.001
It wasn't in French, but look!

06:18.086 --> 06:19.337
Same image.

06:21.380 --> 06:23.299
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

06:23.382 --> 06:25.426
-How much was it?
-SUSAN: Oh, it was nothing.

06:25.510 --> 06:28.262
Twenty euros?
It's not an original.

06:28.346 --> 06:31.933
CHRISTOPHER: You know, Susan,
even 20 euros,

06:32.016 --> 06:34.227
there'll be a final demand
for the gas in there,

06:34.310 --> 06:35.686
and I'm the one
who's gotta open them

06:35.770 --> 06:37.021
and sort it out.

06:39.273 --> 06:41.651
-Is that from Gérard?
-You open it.

06:41.734 --> 06:43.611
SUSAN: Well, no,
it's-- it's for you.

06:44.070 --> 06:45.196
Hmm.

06:48.533 --> 06:50.910
(PAPER RUSTLING)

06:55.498 --> 06:57.959
My God. A hundred euro.

06:58.042 --> 06:59.919
See, crosspatch? Didn't I say?

07:00.002 --> 07:02.922
Things around here
are about to change.

07:03.005 --> 07:04.549
Well, it's only a hundred,
Susan.

07:04.632 --> 07:06.634
-But it's a start, isn't it?
-Of what?

07:08.636 --> 07:10.888
We're way behind on the rent,
and if I don't get a job--

07:10.972 --> 07:13.307
But you will get a job.
That's what I mean.

07:15.977 --> 07:19.605
Yes, well, I'm trying...
trying my hardest.

07:21.149 --> 07:23.401
Come on, then. What's Gérard
got to say for himself?

07:25.570 --> 07:27.321
Read it out loud. I'm listening.

07:27.405 --> 07:28.739
I'll look at it later.

07:28.823 --> 07:32.368
-(FOOTSTEPS RECEDE)
-♪ (OPERA MUSIC PLAYS) ♪

07:32.451 --> 07:37.081
(PAPER RUSTLING)

07:39.250 --> 07:42.837
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACH)

07:47.300 --> 07:51.304
(GUNSHOT ECHOES)

07:53.723 --> 07:56.934
(LOUDER GUNSHOT ECHOES)

07:58.060 --> 08:05.026
-(WIND HOWLS)
-♪ (OPERA MUSIC PLAYS) ♪

08:17.288 --> 08:18.664
CHRISTOPHER: Susan?

08:23.044 --> 08:24.378
Why don't you, uh...

08:27.381 --> 08:29.967
Why don't you put
that thing up? (EXHALES)

08:30.051 --> 08:32.929
Silly, keeping it hidden away
now you've got it.

08:34.013 --> 08:35.932
Yes. Good idea.

08:37.350 --> 08:40.436
Who wouldn't give
this handsome man a job, hey?

08:40.519 --> 08:42.897
We'll celebrate afterwards
in the café.

08:42.980 --> 08:44.941
-(SPEAKING IN FRENCH)
-(CHUCKLES)

08:48.569 --> 08:53.658
♪ (REFLECTIVE MUSIC PLAYS) ♪

08:56.327 --> 08:57.995
-(INDISTINCT CHATTER)
-(MACHINE BUZZES)

08:58.079 --> 09:01.916
-(ELEVATOR BELL RINGS)
-(DOORS OPEN)

09:01.999 --> 09:03.709
(IN FRENCH ACCENT)
Christopher Edwards?

09:03.793 --> 09:06.796
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

09:08.589 --> 09:10.258
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

09:14.553 --> 09:21.644
MANAGER: (SPEAKING FRENCH)

09:30.319 --> 09:35.491
(CONTINUES SPEAKING FRENCH)

09:53.217 --> 09:56.220
Vous pouvez répéter la question?

09:59.932 --> 10:01.225
S'il vous plaît.

10:04.437 --> 10:08.607
♪ (SOMBER MUSIC PLAYS) ♪

10:31.464 --> 10:33.591
(WHISPERS) Go on, Chris.
You can do it.

10:38.804 --> 10:42.933
-(INDISTINCT CHATTER)
-(DUCKS QUACK)

11:06.290 --> 11:07.750
SUSAN: Mon cher, Chris.

11:08.584 --> 11:11.003
Please find enclosed 100 euros,

11:11.087 --> 11:15.466
a small token of my gratitude
for your eternal friendship.

11:15.549 --> 11:19.762
As you will know from my movie,
we have a saying in France,

11:19.845 --> 11:21.931
"La vie en rose."

11:22.014 --> 11:23.349
The meaning of this phrase

11:23.432 --> 11:26.310
is to look up at the stars
instead of in the gutter,

11:27.520 --> 11:29.605
to see the beauty
that exists in life,

11:29.688 --> 11:32.566
even when
it is difficult to find...

11:32.650 --> 11:36.779
perhaps sometimes
even when it is not there.

11:36.862 --> 11:41.742
This is the purpose of stories
and the purpose of cinema,

11:41.826 --> 11:45.871
but more than this,
it is the purpose of love,

11:45.955 --> 11:50.334
and to be loved is the most
beautiful thing in the world.

11:50.418 --> 11:53.963
Yours sincerely,
Gérard Depardieu.

11:58.884 --> 12:00.219
(EXHALES)

12:02.555 --> 12:05.808
-(INDISTINCT CHATTER)
-(TRAIN SCREECHES)

12:05.891 --> 12:09.854
(SIREN BLARES IN DISTANCE)

12:14.024 --> 12:18.028
-(INDISTINCT CHATTER OVER PA)
-♪ (SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYS) ♪

12:31.208 --> 12:33.752
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

12:34.503 --> 12:38.340
♪ (PEACEFUL MUSIC PLAYS) ♪

12:38.424 --> 12:40.801
(BIRDS CHIRP)

13:01.697 --> 13:04.492
-(INDISTINCT CHATTER)
-(PHONE RINGING TONE TRILLS)

13:07.411 --> 13:08.954
(PHONE RINGING TONE TRILLS)

13:12.166 --> 13:15.628
-(PHONE IS PICKED UP)
-CHRISTOPHER: Hello?

13:15.711 --> 13:17.421
-TABITHA EDWARDS: Hello?
-CHRISTOPHER: Is that Tabitha?

13:17.505 --> 13:19.298
TABITHA: Speaking. Who's that?

13:19.381 --> 13:21.717
TABITHA: That's not you,
is it Chris?

13:21.800 --> 13:23.511
-Yeah. It's me.
-TABITHA: Chris?

13:23.928 --> 13:25.262
Yes.

13:25.346 --> 13:27.723
Uh... Um... (EXHALES)

13:27.806 --> 13:30.351
-(INDISTINCT CHATTER OVER PA)
-(EXHALES)

13:30.976 --> 13:32.895
(HESITATES)

13:32.978 --> 13:35.231
Listen, I'm sorry
it's been so long. (CHUCKLES)

13:35.314 --> 13:38.734
-TABITHA: Where are you?
-Uh... I'm-- I'm in France.

13:38.817 --> 13:41.529
-TABITHA: Are you with Susan?
-Yeah.

13:41.612 --> 13:44.698
I've just-- I've just been
for a-- a-- a-- a job interview,

13:44.782 --> 13:45.908
actually.

13:47.618 --> 13:51.038
Yeah, a-- a fairly senior
credit control position.

13:52.289 --> 13:55.084
You know, but the truth is,
what with the, um...

13:57.836 --> 14:00.422
the, um, the language barrier,

14:00.506 --> 14:03.634
um... we-- we're in a bit
of financial, um...

14:05.386 --> 14:07.680
you know-- Uh...
What am I saying? (HESITATES)

14:07.763 --> 14:10.599
There's--
There's this cashflow situation,

14:10.683 --> 14:13.769
um, and believe me, we-- we--
we-- we're very grateful

14:13.852 --> 14:17.147
for all the help
you've given us in the past.

14:18.023 --> 14:20.234
-(METAL CLANKS)
-(GROANS)

14:20.317 --> 14:21.777
-TABITHA: Chris?
-Oh, um...

14:21.860 --> 14:24.071
-TABITHA: Is everything okay?
-No, I'm sorry. I'm still here.

14:24.154 --> 14:25.281
Yeah, um...

14:26.657 --> 14:31.245
(LIPS SMACKING) Uh...
It's just, I need you to...

14:31.328 --> 14:34.206
promise me something,
Tabitha. Um...

14:35.624 --> 14:38.627
You see, I've-- I've-- I've done
something rather silly...

14:39.545 --> 14:40.963
and it might sound bad,

14:41.046 --> 14:44.800
might sound very bad, even,
but it's not what it seems.

14:45.718 --> 14:47.219
Not at all.
It's not what it seems,

14:47.303 --> 14:50.472
and, um, just needs a little bit
of clearing up, that's all.

14:50.556 --> 14:54.351
So... that's why I need you
to promise me.

14:54.435 --> 14:57.646
I need you to promise me

14:57.730 --> 14:59.815
that you won't tell the police.

14:59.898 --> 15:02.359
There you go. Can you
promise me that, Tabitha?

15:02.985 --> 15:04.528
Uh... Because I can't...

15:07.448 --> 15:12.328
I can't let Susan down.

15:12.411 --> 15:13.829
Do you understand?

15:15.873 --> 15:16.999
She's...

15:21.086 --> 15:24.715
She's very, uh, fragile, yes.

15:24.798 --> 15:27.343
TABITHA: Just tell me
what you need, Christopher.

15:27.426 --> 15:29.720
I'm always here for you,
you know that.

15:30.220 --> 15:31.597
(EXHALES)

15:34.933 --> 15:36.393
SUSAN: So, how was it?

15:36.477 --> 15:38.020
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

15:38.103 --> 15:39.563
Yes. (EXHALES)

15:39.647 --> 15:41.982
It's, uh... (EXHALES)

15:42.066 --> 15:45.819
-Yes. Hard to tell, isn't it?
-Yeah. But good, do you think?

15:47.071 --> 15:49.657
Uh... Well, my head's
a bit, um...

15:51.992 --> 15:54.495
-but yes.
-Oh, I knew it.

15:54.578 --> 15:55.996
-Do you want a coffee?
-Yeah.

15:56.080 --> 15:57.373
Okay.

15:57.456 --> 15:58.749
Oh, excusez-moi.

15:59.833 --> 16:01.710
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

16:01.794 --> 16:03.545
-WAITRESS: (SPEAKS FRENCH)
-Merci.

16:04.463 --> 16:06.048
(INHALES)

16:06.131 --> 16:08.425
Yeah, I was actually just, uh...

16:11.637 --> 16:16.684
I was just thinking. (EXHALES)
Supposing I do get this job...

16:16.767 --> 16:19.978
I mean, I still wouldn't be paid
for a few weeks, would I?

16:21.188 --> 16:24.233
We're behind on the rent.
And it--

16:24.316 --> 16:25.734
it's not like other times,
Susan.

16:25.818 --> 16:28.112
We're... We could be in...

16:29.029 --> 16:30.948
-Merci.
-Thank you. Merci.

16:31.031 --> 16:32.449
We could be in trouble.

16:33.742 --> 16:34.743
So...

16:36.120 --> 16:38.789
I was thinking, maybe,
to take the pressure off,

16:38.872 --> 16:41.417
we could try
to borrow some money.

16:43.627 --> 16:44.920
You know, I could ask

16:45.003 --> 16:47.297
my stepmother, Tabitha.
She's, uh...

16:49.007 --> 16:50.426
You think?
She's family, isn't she?

16:50.509 --> 16:51.552
No.

16:51.635 --> 16:53.429
-Really? I mean, would you--
-But no one knows

16:53.512 --> 16:54.847
where we are or why.

16:55.681 --> 16:58.434
And you'd possibly have to tell,

16:58.517 --> 17:00.561
wouldn't you?
You'd have to explain a little

17:00.644 --> 17:02.146
why we're here, and then,

17:02.229 --> 17:03.939
-she could tell the police,
couldn't she?
-(SIGHS)

17:04.022 --> 17:06.859
-SUSAN: Not we've done
anything wrong.
-The police?

17:06.942 --> 17:09.695
Why would she do that?
I don't think there's any danger
of her doing that.

17:10.612 --> 17:12.614
-She's family.
-No, Chris.

17:14.616 --> 17:17.077
-(INDISTINCT CHATTER)
-♪ (OMINOUS MUSIC PLAYS) ♪

17:18.746 --> 17:20.956
Look, we're doing fine.

17:21.039 --> 17:23.751
We're just going through a bit
of a sticky patch, that's all.

17:27.921 --> 17:32.301
Yeah. Yeah, you're right.
(INHALES)

17:32.384 --> 17:34.595
(EXHALES) Forget I mentioned it.
It's a silly idea.

17:34.678 --> 17:37.181
-Silly.
-(PHONE RINGING TONE TRILLS)

17:38.640 --> 17:40.017
(PHONE RINGING TONE TRILLS)

17:41.727 --> 17:43.270
(PHONE RINGING TONE TRILLS)

17:43.353 --> 17:45.731
OPERATOR: Thank you for calling
Nottinghamshire Police.

17:45.814 --> 17:48.025
Please leave a message
after the tone.

17:48.734 --> 17:49.651
(BEEP)

17:49.735 --> 17:52.780
TABITHA: My name
is Doctor Tabitha Edwards.

17:52.863 --> 17:55.199
I'm calling to report
something rather...

17:56.492 --> 17:58.660
Well, I don't know
what to make of it, frankly.

18:00.704 --> 18:03.999
My stepson just told me
over the telephone...

18:04.082 --> 18:05.209
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

18:05.292 --> 18:08.837
...that he buried
his wife's parents

18:08.921 --> 18:12.424
in a garden near Nottingham
fifteen years ago.

18:15.010 --> 18:17.638
So, I'm just curious to know

18:17.721 --> 18:19.515
if there were
any reports of a couple

18:19.598 --> 18:23.101
by the name of William
and Patricia Wycherley

18:23.185 --> 18:25.229
going missing around that time?

18:26.939 --> 18:30.275
(TRAFFIC NOISE)

18:30.359 --> 18:32.402
-EMMA LANCING: Sir?
-TONY COLLIER: No.

18:34.071 --> 18:35.614
-Sir?
-COLLIER: Go away!

18:35.697 --> 18:37.658
Fuck off, Emma.
I'm having my lunch.

18:37.741 --> 18:40.077
Have you got a minute, sir?

18:40.160 --> 18:42.246
We've just received a tip.
There are two bodies buried

18:42.329 --> 18:44.623
in a back garden
in a house in Mansfield.

18:44.706 --> 18:46.125
Woman called Tabitha Edwards...

18:46.208 --> 18:47.501
-was informed yesterday...
-(EXHALES)

18:47.584 --> 18:49.211
...by her stepson, Christopher.

18:49.294 --> 18:51.380
-When?
-LANCING: Fifteen years ago.

18:51.463 --> 18:53.257
Fifteen years? Fuck off.

18:53.340 --> 18:55.134
Stop telling me
to fuck off please, sir.

18:55.217 --> 18:56.176
(SLURPS, SPITS)

18:56.260 --> 18:58.428
Bloody hell.
Why is this so fucking hot?

18:58.512 --> 19:00.222
-(INHALES)
-Well, it's a flask, sir.

19:00.305 --> 19:02.683
Fucking Mount Etna, that is.
Ridiculous.

19:02.766 --> 19:06.186
-Can't feel my fucking mouth.
-It's his in-laws
apparently, sir.

19:06.270 --> 19:08.438
-His what?
-The bodies.

19:08.522 --> 19:10.023
Says he didn't
actually kill them.

19:10.107 --> 19:11.608
Says it was an accident.

19:11.692 --> 19:13.026
Rang to ask his stepmom
for some money

19:13.110 --> 19:15.487
-and then he just sort of
spilled the beans.
-Right.

19:15.571 --> 19:18.240
-Does he know that we know?
-She's made him aware, yeah.

19:18.323 --> 19:21.618
Just, um, sent him
an email, apparently.

19:21.702 --> 19:23.287
Sent an email?

19:23.370 --> 19:26.790
What? "Dear Christopher,
I've told the fucking police"?

19:26.874 --> 19:30.210
CHRISTOPHER: I told her
in strict confidence!

19:30.294 --> 19:31.753
I asked her not to tell anyone.

19:31.837 --> 19:33.964
I'm as disappointed as you are.
I'm...

19:35.090 --> 19:37.134
I'm-- I'm disgusted, actually.

19:39.970 --> 19:42.097
Darling, she wasn't gonna
send any money

19:42.180 --> 19:43.599
unless I told her
what was going on

19:43.682 --> 19:46.977
and why we needed it.
Put yourself in my shoes.

19:47.060 --> 19:49.229
What was I supposed to do?
We'll be living on the streets,

19:49.313 --> 19:52.482
eating croissants
out of rubbish bins next!

19:52.566 --> 19:53.942
Is that what you want?

19:56.695 --> 19:58.572
We'd still be together though,
wouldn't we?

20:04.453 --> 20:05.621
It's okay.

20:07.539 --> 20:08.874
Just have to move again.

20:09.499 --> 20:13.170
(FOOTSTEPS RECEDE)

20:16.256 --> 20:17.799
(BREATHES SHAKILY)

20:19.843 --> 20:22.554
(OBJECTS CLATTER)

20:26.224 --> 20:28.852
(OBJECTS CLATTER)

20:33.607 --> 20:35.108
(GLASS SHATTERS)

20:46.328 --> 20:47.829
-CHRISTOPHER: Susan--
-SUSAN: (SHOUTS) No!

20:47.913 --> 20:50.290
You were supposed
to protect me!

20:50.374 --> 20:55.545
I have protected you!
I am. I'm trying!

20:57.214 --> 20:59.007
But we both knew
this day would come.

20:59.091 --> 21:01.551
But it's not your decision,
Chris! There are two of us here!

21:01.635 --> 21:03.428
We're in this together,
aren't we?

21:04.846 --> 21:05.973
(SHOUTS) Aren't we?

21:07.265 --> 21:08.308
Yes.

21:08.392 --> 21:10.894
And now, after all this time,
I'd do it for you.

21:10.978 --> 21:13.230
I'd live on the streets for you.
I'd eat rubbish for you!

21:13.313 --> 21:14.982
I'd eat a croissant
out of a bin for you.

21:15.065 --> 21:18.026
-CHRISTOPHER: Well, we're not
quite there yet.
-But I would, though!

21:21.071 --> 21:22.197
(QUIETLY) Yeah.

21:26.493 --> 21:28.829
CHRISTOPHER: Let's get this
cleared up, shall we?

21:31.665 --> 21:33.375
Then how about a film?

21:34.751 --> 21:36.253
Would you like to watch a film?

21:41.258 --> 21:42.509
(SIGHS)

21:45.303 --> 21:47.097
(CAR APPROACHES)

21:47.180 --> 21:50.017
-(INDISTINCT CHATTER)
-(DOG BARKS)

21:50.100 --> 21:52.644
PAUL WILKIE: Yeah,
that's it there, number seven.

21:52.728 --> 21:55.022
LANCING: It's not number seven,
mate. It's number five.

21:56.398 --> 21:57.691
WILKIE: Oh, right.

21:58.775 --> 22:00.444
LANCING: That's the house
over there.

22:03.905 --> 22:04.990
So, shall we park up

22:05.073 --> 22:06.575
-over there, then?
-Yeah. All right, all right.

22:06.658 --> 22:07.951
I'm on it, I'm on it.

22:09.494 --> 22:11.580
(DOORBELL RINGS)

22:11.663 --> 22:13.040
LANCING: Just don't make
a scene.

22:13.123 --> 22:14.499
WILKIE: Why would I make
a scene?

22:14.583 --> 22:15.751
LANCING: Because you're a twat.

22:15.834 --> 22:17.544
-WILKIE: You're a twat.
-(KNOCKS ON DOOR)

22:17.627 --> 22:20.505
LANCING: Why are you doing that?
I just rang the bell.

22:20.589 --> 22:22.257
Can you stand a bit further
away from me, please?

22:22.340 --> 22:24.634
WILKIE: What you on about?
I'm not even standing that-- Oh!

22:25.719 --> 22:27.512
-Afternoon.
-Good afternoon, sir.

22:27.596 --> 22:29.723
Sorry to bother you.
We're from Nottingham Police.

22:29.806 --> 22:32.851
We're following up a report
of a historic crime in the area

22:32.934 --> 22:35.020
and, uh, wonder if we could have
a quick chat.

22:35.103 --> 22:38.231
-DANNY: Oh, right. Um...
-If that's not too much trouble.

22:38.315 --> 22:39.983
DANNY: No, sure. Uh...

22:40.067 --> 22:42.402
Come in. I've got my youngest
asleep upstairs, though,

22:42.486 --> 22:44.738
if you don't mind creeping.

22:44.821 --> 22:46.114
LANCING: All right, no problem.

22:46.198 --> 22:48.617
-Perhaps we could go
through to the garden?
-Yeah, sure.

22:48.700 --> 22:50.702
WILKIE: Yes, assuming
you've got a garden.

22:51.161 --> 22:52.329
You what?

22:52.412 --> 22:53.872
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

22:53.955 --> 22:54.956
Yeah.

22:58.460 --> 22:59.503
(QUIETLY) Twat.

23:00.837 --> 23:03.423
How long you've been here,
if you don't mind me asking?

23:03.507 --> 23:05.634
(SIGHS) Going on eight years.

23:05.717 --> 23:07.010
LANCING: Nice neighborhood?

23:07.719 --> 23:09.221
Yeah, it's nice enough.

23:09.304 --> 23:10.931
Pretty quiet, to be honest
with you,

23:11.014 --> 23:13.475
but, uh, well, we like it.

23:13.558 --> 23:16.645
WILKIE: Do you know who lived
here before, by any chance?

23:16.728 --> 23:20.023
A elderly couple, apparently.
I'd have to check the, um...

23:20.107 --> 23:22.275
-Wycherley?
-DANNY: Huh?

23:23.985 --> 23:25.445
-Was it, uh...
-(LIGHTER CLICKING)

23:25.529 --> 23:28.448
...William and Patricia
Wycherley, by any chance?

23:28.532 --> 23:31.284
DANNY: Yeah, rings a bell. Um...

23:31.368 --> 23:32.786
Why? Is this about them?

23:33.537 --> 23:34.913
NIGEL: It wasn't me.

23:34.996 --> 23:36.998
♪ (PLAYFUL MUSIC PLAYS) ♪

23:37.082 --> 23:39.626
NIGEL: Whatever it is
you're investigating, officers,

23:39.709 --> 23:41.044
it wasn't me.

23:41.128 --> 23:42.337
LANCING: Hello, there.

23:42.420 --> 23:45.257
DANNY: That's, uh--
That's Nigel.

23:45.340 --> 23:47.425
He likes to talk to us
through the hedge.

23:47.509 --> 23:48.635
All right, Nige?

23:48.718 --> 23:50.512
NIGEL: Well, I should be happy
to move to the gap

23:50.595 --> 23:52.347
if that's preferable, officers.

23:52.430 --> 23:55.225
There's a gap just down there.
Shall we do that?

24:06.570 --> 24:08.613
This is what I mean by a gap.

24:08.697 --> 24:11.992
It's quite handy
for talking across gardens.

24:12.075 --> 24:14.619
DANNY: What's on the barbie
today, then, Nige?

24:14.703 --> 24:17.164
Been having quite a few,
so I've noticed. (CHUCKLES)

24:17.247 --> 24:19.332
NIGEL: Well, you're always
welcome to join us, Danny,

24:19.416 --> 24:20.584
you know that.

24:22.127 --> 24:25.380
Briony! There's a couple
of police officers here

24:25.463 --> 24:28.592
asking poor Danny some questions
about the Wycherleys.

24:28.675 --> 24:30.719
Could you bring out
some more bangers?

24:30.802 --> 24:32.262
I think it'd be fair to say

24:32.345 --> 24:34.472
they were slightly
peculiar neighbors.

24:34.556 --> 24:36.975
Although we didn't see a great
deal of them, did we, Bri?

24:37.058 --> 24:38.059
No, not much.

24:38.143 --> 24:39.269
-We heard them mostly.
-Yeah.

24:39.352 --> 24:41.146
-Playing that strange organ.
-Oh!

24:41.229 --> 24:43.607
Morning, afternoon, evening.

24:43.690 --> 24:45.775
Apart from that, they kept
themselves to themselves.

24:45.859 --> 24:46.860
Hmm.

24:46.943 --> 24:49.821
Do you need more ketchup,
officer? It's homemade.

24:49.905 --> 24:52.199
Mm. No. I'm good thanks.
These are...

24:52.282 --> 24:54.117
These are really nice.
Thank you. Hmm.

24:54.201 --> 24:56.203
So, you can hear
quite well then, can you?

24:56.286 --> 24:57.287
Your neighbors.

24:57.370 --> 24:59.831
NIGEL: Oh, very well.
You can hear everything.

24:59.915 --> 25:03.251
Anything untoward or unusual
while the Wycherleys were here?

25:03.335 --> 25:06.254
NIGEL: Ah, it's just the normal
sort of bickering, I suppose.

25:06.338 --> 25:08.089
Occasional rows.

25:08.173 --> 25:11.009
(GASPS) Oh, they were quite
funny together, mind.

25:11.092 --> 25:14.804
You see, on the rare occasion
that you'd see them out,

25:14.888 --> 25:17.015
on the way to the shops,
for example,

25:17.098 --> 25:22.020
Patricia would walk two
or three yards behind William.

25:22.103 --> 25:26.691
A sort of Victorian thing,
like she was his chattel.

25:26.775 --> 25:29.945
So, I-- I-- I don't know
if that could be used as a...

25:30.028 --> 25:31.905
clue of some kind.

25:32.405 --> 25:35.158
(RAIN PATTERING)

25:35.242 --> 25:37.494
I'll bear that in mind,
thank you. (INHALES)

25:37.577 --> 25:41.414
Do you know what came of them?
When they left, where they went?

25:41.498 --> 25:43.917
Blackpool then Ireland's
what we heard. Yeah.

25:44.000 --> 25:45.293
-For the air.
-Yeah. Yeah.

25:45.377 --> 25:47.963
-Big smokers, both of them.
-NIGEL: Left their daughter

25:48.046 --> 25:49.881
and their son-in-law
to look after the place.

25:49.965 --> 25:53.468
-Son-in-law mainly, Chris. Uh...
-And, um,

25:53.551 --> 25:55.595
when would the Wycherleys
have gone to Blackpool?

25:55.679 --> 25:58.473
-NIGEL: Oh, let's see,
what, ten?
-BRIONY: Fift...

25:58.556 --> 25:59.975
-Fifteen.
-Fifteen. Fifteen years ago.

26:00.058 --> 26:02.560
-Hmm.
-Yeah, well before
they actually sold the place.

26:02.644 --> 26:04.688
It were Christopher
who told us they'd gone.

26:04.771 --> 26:06.982
He were the only one we'd chat
with from time to time.

26:07.065 --> 26:08.775
Yeah, when they were
doing the garden.

26:12.028 --> 26:13.613
-What?
-What about the...

26:13.697 --> 26:16.533
-(WHISPERS)
-Oh! (CHUCKLES)

26:16.616 --> 26:19.035
Uh-- Yeah, yeah,
another funny thing, actually.

26:19.119 --> 26:20.829
There was a morning,
about that time,

26:20.912 --> 26:23.415
when I woke up early,
as I sometimes do,

26:23.498 --> 26:25.625
and I looked out my window,

26:25.709 --> 26:30.839
and I saw Chris digging a hole
in the Wycherleys' garden.

26:30.922 --> 26:33.300
Quite a deep hole.
Very deep, in fact.

26:33.383 --> 26:35.844
Now, he was probably just
planting those rhododendrons

26:35.927 --> 26:38.054
that you'd seen round
at Danny's but, uh,

26:38.138 --> 26:39.514
we joked about it, didn't we?

26:39.597 --> 26:41.725
'Cause we said he's probably
burying his in-laws. (LAUGHS)

26:41.808 --> 26:45.854
Because it was about that time
that they'd, uh, moved away.

26:45.937 --> 26:49.149
So, I don't know
if that could be used as a...

26:50.066 --> 26:51.651
some kind of clue?

26:53.903 --> 26:56.239
♪ (SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYS) ♪

27:00.910 --> 27:02.412
(DOG BARKS)

27:02.495 --> 27:04.331
-OFFICER 1: Let him through.
Let him through.
-Go on, you go out.

27:04.414 --> 27:05.915
-OFFICER 1: Keep going.
-Edward, on your scooter.

27:05.999 --> 27:07.125
Go through. Yeah.

27:07.208 --> 27:09.502
DANNY: Hold on. Edward,
hold on, wait for your sister.

27:12.797 --> 27:15.675
(INDISTINCT CHATTER
OVER POLICE RADIO)

27:15.759 --> 27:17.052
COLLIER: Dear, Mr. Edwards,

27:17.135 --> 27:20.180
please forgive
my contacting you directly...

27:20.263 --> 27:22.140
but your stepmother,
Dr. Tabitha Edwards,

27:22.223 --> 27:23.558
has been kind enough
to pass along

27:23.641 --> 27:25.185
your email address.

27:25.268 --> 27:26.728
She indicated you may be
in possession

27:26.811 --> 27:29.189
of some information
of possible interest to us

27:29.272 --> 27:31.900
and if you'd be good enough
to share your telephone number,

27:31.983 --> 27:33.193
we'd very much like
to speak with you

27:33.276 --> 27:35.236
at your earliest convenience.

27:35.320 --> 27:37.655
Even better would be
the opportunity

27:37.739 --> 27:39.866
to arrange
for a personal interview,

27:39.949 --> 27:41.576
although Dr. Edwards informs us

27:41.659 --> 27:44.371
that you may
currently be residing abroad.

27:44.454 --> 27:46.623
I want to reassure you that
in that event,

27:46.706 --> 27:48.666
we don't believe
it's in anyone's interests

27:48.750 --> 27:50.627
to trouble
the local authorities.

27:50.710 --> 27:53.797
Yours truly,
Detective Chief Inspector
Tony Collier.

27:54.714 --> 27:57.592
♪ (OMINOUS MUSIC PLAYS) ♪

27:59.052 --> 28:00.553
AMY FOWLER: (ON TV)
Why are you stopping?

28:00.637 --> 28:02.680
It's no good.
I've got to go back, Amy.

28:02.764 --> 28:03.890
Why?

28:03.973 --> 28:06.309
(SIGHS) This is crazy.
I haven't even got any guns.

28:06.393 --> 28:08.019
AMY FOWLER: (ON TV)
Then let's go on. Hurry.

28:08.103 --> 28:10.021
-(BIRDS CHIRP)
-WILL KANE: (ON TV) No.

28:10.105 --> 28:11.022
They're making me run.

28:11.106 --> 28:13.149
I've never run
from anybody before.

28:15.110 --> 28:17.362
♪ (OMINOUS MUSIC CONTINUES) ♪

28:22.951 --> 28:24.536
(DOG BARKS)

28:26.204 --> 28:27.580
THOMAS MITCHELL:
There's gonna be fighting

28:27.664 --> 28:29.999
when Kane and Miller meet.

28:30.083 --> 28:31.751
-And somebody's gonna get hurt.
-(CLOCK TICKING)

28:31.835 --> 28:34.045
-That's for sure.
-(CLOCK TICKING)

28:34.129 --> 28:37.048
(TRAIN HORN BLARES)

28:40.885 --> 28:43.471
-ACTOR 1: Everything ready?
-ACTOR 2: Sure, just the way
you want it, Frank.

28:43.555 --> 28:45.974
ACTOR 3: Yeah, we've got
your gun over here.

28:46.057 --> 28:47.725
ACTOR 1: Let's get started,
then.

28:48.435 --> 28:50.687
(HORSES GALLOP IN FILM)

28:52.439 --> 28:56.067
♪ (DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYS) ♪

28:58.653 --> 29:02.449
♪ (SPAGHETTI WESTERN
MUSIC PLAYS) ♪

29:02.949 --> 29:05.201
(GUN IS COCKED)

29:05.285 --> 29:07.537
-CHRISTOPHER: Dear DCI Collier.
-(GUNSHOT)

29:07.620 --> 29:09.789
Thank you
for your considerate message.

29:09.873 --> 29:12.292
My wife Susan and I
would be delighted

29:12.375 --> 29:14.335
to assist you
in any way we can...

29:14.419 --> 29:15.837
-(GUNSHOT)
-CHRISTOPHER:
...and to put this

29:15.920 --> 29:18.298
whole matter behind us
once and for all.

29:18.381 --> 29:20.675
We agree that it's
in everyone's interests

29:20.758 --> 29:24.179
to avoid involving
the French police.

29:24.262 --> 29:26.681
I'm afraid, however,
that our return to England

29:26.764 --> 29:29.601
may not happen as soon
as you might prefer.

29:29.684 --> 29:30.852
-Good afternoon.
-(INDISTINCT CLAMOR)

29:30.935 --> 29:32.604
How many leads do you have
besides the garden?

29:32.687 --> 29:35.190
CHRISTOPHER: I'm sure that you
understand that my first duty

29:35.273 --> 29:36.566
is to my wife.

29:36.649 --> 29:38.693
She is of a very fragile
disposition

29:38.776 --> 29:41.237
and we have been leading
a peaceful...

29:41.321 --> 29:42.780
existence here in France.

29:42.864 --> 29:45.909
I'd be worried about inflicting
unnecessary stress

29:45.992 --> 29:49.037
and it could take her some time
to come round to the idea

29:49.120 --> 29:51.998
of leaving this country
to return to the UK.

29:52.081 --> 29:55.168
-(INDISTINCT CLAMOR ON TV)
-CHRISTOPHER: Nevertheless,
do let's stay in touch.

29:55.251 --> 29:56.836
We look forward
to the opportunity

29:56.920 --> 29:59.631
to clear our names
as soon as possible.

29:59.714 --> 30:02.008
You have my word.

30:02.091 --> 30:04.552
Yours very sincerely,

30:04.636 --> 30:07.305
Christopher Edwards.

30:12.602 --> 30:17.440
(GUNSHOT ECHOES LOUDLY)

30:17.524 --> 30:21.986
♪ (TRIUMPHANT MUSIC PLAYS) ♪

30:23.029 --> 30:26.824
♪ (MUSIC BECOMES SERENE) ♪

30:33.289 --> 30:36.834
(CAMERA FOCUSES, SHUTTER CLICKS)

30:36.918 --> 30:39.546
COLLIER: In answer
to the question
on everyone's mind,

30:39.629 --> 30:41.089
-I can confirm that...
-(CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKS)

30:41.172 --> 30:43.299
...yesterday morning,
two bodies were found buried

30:43.383 --> 30:46.511
in the back garden
of a house in Mansfield.

30:46.594 --> 30:51.140
At present, we cannot confirm
the identities of the deceased,

30:51.224 --> 30:53.226
nor do we know
the cause of death

30:53.309 --> 30:55.937
or the circumstances under which
they came to be buried

30:56.020 --> 30:57.605
in that location.

30:57.689 --> 30:59.566
That being said,
we do have some leads

30:59.649 --> 31:02.360
and we hope to be making
significant progress

31:02.443 --> 31:04.737
-over the coming days.
-(INDISTINCT CLAMOR)

31:04.821 --> 31:07.574
LANCING: "Do let's keep
in touch." I'm sorry,
but what is that?

31:07.657 --> 31:09.242
COLLIER: Psychopath.
Written all over it.

31:09.325 --> 31:10.451
LANCING: Why can't we just get
a warrant,

31:10.535 --> 31:12.412
have the French track them down
and pick them up

31:12.495 --> 31:13.705
before they get away?

31:13.788 --> 31:16.249
What we arresting them for,
Emma? Writing a weird email?

31:16.332 --> 31:19.168
LANCING: Prevention of a lawful
and decent burial?

31:19.252 --> 31:20.378
Double murder?

31:20.461 --> 31:21.796
Hey! Good one!

31:21.879 --> 31:24.591
Let's go and arrest them,
then, shall we? Off we pop!

31:24.674 --> 31:26.092
Oh, hang on a minute.

31:26.175 --> 31:28.094
Where the fuck
did the murders take place?

31:28.177 --> 31:31.139
When the fuck? Who the fuck
was involved? How the fuck?

31:31.222 --> 31:32.640
European Arrest Warrant.

31:32.724 --> 31:35.143
Because, thank you, Paul...

31:35.226 --> 31:37.270
that's what we need
for a European Arrest Warrant,

31:37.353 --> 31:38.396
minimum.

31:38.479 --> 31:40.189
So, they can just stay there
as long as they like?

31:40.273 --> 31:42.233
Yes. He's thick
as two short planks

31:42.317 --> 31:43.943
-and he knows that.
-Cheers, mate.

31:44.027 --> 31:45.945
At the minute, all we've got
are those bullets,

31:46.029 --> 31:47.822
a nutty professor
who got a dodgy phone call

31:47.905 --> 31:50.908
from some bloke in Lille,
a pair of rickety old skeletons

31:50.992 --> 31:53.161
in a back yard,
buried God knows when,

31:53.244 --> 31:55.038
and a vague proclamation
of innocence

31:55.121 --> 31:57.707
from a man who writes
very polite emails

31:57.790 --> 31:59.208
to the police.

31:59.292 --> 32:01.336
So, either we come up
with some hard evidence

32:01.419 --> 32:03.421
or Croque Madame
and her pen-pal Muppet husband

32:03.504 --> 32:05.256
can carry on
with their French bloody holiday

32:05.340 --> 32:07.425
for as long
as they damn well please.

32:10.303 --> 32:13.306
I'll see you in ten minutes.
I'm getting a fucking sandwich.

32:17.935 --> 32:20.980
LANCING: So what do we make
of this "fragile" business then?

32:21.064 --> 32:24.233
"She's of a very
fragile disposition."

32:24.317 --> 32:26.986
He's just saying whatever comes
into his head, isn't he?

32:27.070 --> 32:28.237
To fuck with us.

32:29.072 --> 32:30.281
I hate that.

32:31.074 --> 32:32.659
Fragile people.

32:34.535 --> 32:35.662
All right.

32:36.954 --> 32:38.706
We've got nothing
to go on, do we?

32:39.749 --> 32:42.043
She might not even
be that fragile.

32:42.126 --> 32:45.380
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

32:45.463 --> 32:46.798
But he didn't need to tell
his stepmom

32:46.881 --> 32:49.926
that he'd buried those bodies
in the garden, did he?

32:50.009 --> 32:52.387
He's answering questions
no one's even asked.

32:54.681 --> 32:55.932
And they're not even
his parents,

32:56.015 --> 32:58.476
so what's he doing burying them
in the fucking garden?

32:58.559 --> 33:00.019
If...

33:00.103 --> 33:01.437
If he did bury them.

33:02.814 --> 33:03.815
I don't know.

33:04.982 --> 33:06.234
‘Cause they're heavy?

33:07.193 --> 33:08.444
Oh, it can't just be that.

33:08.528 --> 33:11.531
I've got tits, I could dig
a fucking hole if I had to.

33:16.244 --> 33:17.495
"Fragile."

33:17.578 --> 33:19.872
I know what fragile
fucking means.

33:19.956 --> 33:22.166
It means you're in charge.

33:22.250 --> 33:25.211
You're the one who gets drunk
and ends up in hospital.

33:25.294 --> 33:27.422
You're the one who gets sad
and lashes out.

33:27.505 --> 33:29.549
You're the pain in the arse,
basically.

33:30.591 --> 33:32.301
(SIGHS HEAVILY)

33:39.517 --> 33:40.727
My, um...

33:42.687 --> 33:44.522
My mom always says
about relationships

33:44.605 --> 33:48.693
that one of you is the gardener
and the other one's the garden.

33:50.319 --> 33:53.531
♪ (OPERA MUSIC PLAYS) ♪

33:54.031 --> 33:55.116
Right.

33:56.576 --> 33:57.744
What does that mean?

34:00.705 --> 34:01.789
Don't know.

34:03.124 --> 34:04.959
I fucking hate gardening.

34:05.042 --> 34:08.504
♪ (OPERA MUSIC CONTINUES) ♪

34:10.047 --> 34:11.841
(SIGHS)

34:11.924 --> 34:14.510
REPORTER: (ON RADIO)
What happened here is unknown,

34:14.594 --> 34:16.304
but over 13 years ago,

34:16.387 --> 34:19.182
two bodies were buried
in this garden.

34:19.265 --> 34:22.310
Only discovered
by police on Thursday,

34:22.393 --> 34:24.312
officers were led to the house

34:24.395 --> 34:26.773
after receiving information
last week

34:26.856 --> 34:31.110
about an alleged incident
in the late 1990s.

34:31.194 --> 34:33.279
COLLIER: (ON TV)
Our enquiries have confirmed

34:33.362 --> 34:36.240
that in 1998, an elderly couple,

34:36.324 --> 34:38.951
named William
and Patricia Wycherley,

34:39.035 --> 34:41.788
resided at the address
in question.

34:41.871 --> 34:43.581
We have, of course,
been in contact

34:43.664 --> 34:45.416
with former neighbors
and relatives

34:45.500 --> 34:46.667
of the Wycherleys,

34:46.751 --> 34:49.754
and they've painted a picture
of a quiet couple

34:49.837 --> 34:52.173
who kept themselves
to their selves,

34:52.256 --> 34:54.467
and who appeared to have

34:54.550 --> 34:56.677
very few close friends
or assoc-- (TV SHUTS OFF)

35:04.101 --> 35:06.270
I didn't finish that crossword.

35:06.354 --> 35:07.271
SUSAN: Oh, well.

35:07.355 --> 35:09.148
We can have another look
at it later.

35:11.150 --> 35:13.444
(INHALES) I've pressed
your suit for you.

35:17.490 --> 35:18.491
Thank you.

35:18.574 --> 35:21.536
In case you get
a second interview for that job.

35:23.079 --> 35:25.832
I won't get a second interview.
It's been a week.

35:25.915 --> 35:27.792
Now, why would you say that?
Why would you give up?

35:27.875 --> 35:30.920
(SHOUTS) Because it was
a terrible interview!

35:33.631 --> 35:34.674
They've all been terrible.

35:34.757 --> 35:38.177
It was a waste of time,
and it was humiliating.

35:43.516 --> 35:47.895
Have the... police replied
to your message?

35:47.979 --> 35:51.023
No, they haven't.
And to tell you the truth...

35:54.610 --> 35:56.487
I just think
that the more we run,

35:56.571 --> 35:58.281
the more guilty we'll seem.

36:00.658 --> 36:01.993
They won't believe us.

36:05.204 --> 36:06.581
I'm going for a shower.

36:06.664 --> 36:10.418
-(FOOTSTEPS RECEDE)
-♪ (SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

36:13.296 --> 36:14.589
(DOOR CLOSES LOUDLY)

36:17.425 --> 36:20.428
Forensics confirms that one
of the bodies is male,

36:20.511 --> 36:22.179
the other is female.

36:22.263 --> 36:25.558
We recovered
two .38-caliber bullets

36:25.641 --> 36:28.311
from each of the wrappings
around the body.

36:28.394 --> 36:32.106
Looks most likely that both
were shot twice in the chest

36:32.190 --> 36:33.482
using the same weapon.

36:33.566 --> 36:36.777
Obviously, we are yet to hear
any more from the Edwardses,

36:36.861 --> 36:40.197
but I think it's fair to say
that whoever killed these people

36:40.281 --> 36:42.241
probably killed them on purpose.

36:42.325 --> 36:46.245
-♪ (OMINOUS MUSIC PLAYS) ♪
-(MIRROR SQUEAKS)

37:00.426 --> 37:04.347
♪ (SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYS) ♪

